Problems with the previous iteration of these designs
Too much digging into dialogs. Disaggregation into per-device settings creates additional work and complexity for the user.
The same display gets represented in multiple different places: in the settings panel, in the display settings dialogs and in the arrange displays dialog.
Separating the settings for each display doesn't make sense when mirroring. In this mode, settings like resolution are shared between all displays.
Display switch shouldn't allow all displays to be turned off at once - one should flip on when the final one is turned off.
Redesign goals

Multiple displays are generally configured with the use case in mind, rather than a set of individual display configurations. For example: "do a presentation using the projector and my laptop", "use my monitors as a workspace". One goal is to reflect these use cases in the UI rather than requiring users to translate their high-level goals into a set of individual device settings.
Surface the most important settings and avoid having to dig into dialogs.
Presentation mode: displays aren't joined and the presentation display is used for content display (presentation slides, photo slideshows, etc).
Tentatively not showing numbers to identify displays here, since it wouldn't look very professional in a presentatation scenario.
It isn't possible to show unique numbers to identify each display when mirroring, so don't show them in this mode.
Natural light filter is disabled when presenting (row becomes insensitive).
